column168: OUR DRIVER STOPPED FOR RAILROAD TRACKS. AS HE WAS STARTING BACK UP TO SPEED, A TRASH HAULER APPROACHED AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. THE TRASH HAULER STRUCK THE AIR PRODUCTS CARGO TANK ON THE RIGHT REAR CORNER, CRUSHED THE CABINET, AND SHEARED OFF 3 CYLINDER VALVES. THE HYDROGEN IGNITED AND RESULTED IN THE SAFETIES OF THE OTHER 6 TUBES (CYLINDERS) RUPTURING AND ADDING TO THE FIRE. ALL NINE TUBES COMPLETELY VENTED. THE AIR PRODUCTS DRIVER HAD SOME BACK PAIN FROM JUMPING FROM THE TRUCK. THE OTHER DRIVER RECEIVED SLIGHT BURNS TO HIS FACE AND A CUT ON HIS ARM, TREATED AT THE SCENE.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD BY RMCAT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AWAITING DISPOSITION. WHEN DRIVER HAD FINISHED UNLOADING HE AND THE OPERATOR THOUGHT THE HOSE WERE EMPTY. WHEN THEY UNHOOKED APPRAX. 2 TO 3 GAL. CAME OUT. AREA WAS CLEANED UP.

1. 40 YARD ROLL-OFF BIN WITH LINER WAS DELIVERED TO NEW UNITED MOTORS. 2. BIN WAS LOADED WITH 500 LBS SLUDGE FILLED DRUM LINERS, DROPPED FROM OVER THE TOP. 3. BIN LINER WAS RIPPED BY THE FALLING BAGGED DRUM LINERS, AND CRACKS DEVELOPED IN FRONT CORNER OF BIN. 4. CUSTOMER CALLED AND NOTIFIED US THAT BIN WAS LEAKING. 5. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PATCH A SMALL SEEPING FRACTURE CRACK IN WELD, AND AS A PRECAUTION PUT VISQUEEN AND ABSORBANT PADS ON THE OUTSIDE OF BIN. THIS ACTION WAS NOT AUTHORIZED BY M P ENVIRONMENTAL. 6. DRIVER THOUGHT THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND LEFT CUSTOMER LOCATION.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: 1. ADDITIONAL TRAINING OF DRIVERS, ESPECIALLY RECENTLY HIRED ONES, THAT UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES ARE DAMAGED CONTAINERS TO BE PICKED UP. 2. LABELING BINS "SOLIDS ONLY, NO LIQUIDS".

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT MAYHILL 66 IN MAYHILL, NM. USING TRUCK PUMP. A VALVE WAS CLOSED ON THE RECEIVING TANK CAUSING BACK PRESSURE ON HOSE AND SUBSEQUENT FAILURE OF HOSE. DRIVER APPLIED DIRT TO THE EFFECTED AREA TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB SPILLED MATERIAL. SITE WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN 24 HOURS BY QUEEN OIL PERSONNEL AND ARE VIEWED AND INSPECTED BY LEONARD MURRAY, ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENTIST/SPECIALIST WITH THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS GOING AROUND LEFT TURN TOO FAST FOR CONDITION OF ROAD. PRODUCT SURGED TO MIGHT, AT SAME TIME DRIVER CUT LEFT TURN SHORT RIDING UP ON CENTER 6" CURB. RESULT TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON RIGHT SIDE. WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED & FUEL LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. AREA CLEAN UP IS UNDER WAY WITH DIRECTION FROM MN PCA COMMISSION AT TIME OF UNHING, ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVE. DRIVER AFTER 1 WEEK SUSPENSION IS RECEIVING TWO WEEKS REMEDIAL TRAINING.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER WENT TO NOTES  IN PLANT TO WEIGH. WHEN HE HIT HIS BUMPERS APPRAX. 1 GAL CAME OUT THE DOME AREA. DOME GASPIT HAD A CUT IN IT. GASPIT WAS REPLACED.

ON 9/10/02, A SMALL LEAK WAS NOTICED ON A TRAILER PARKED AT THE OES BLAINE, MN 10 DAY FACILITY. A ONE GALLON GLASS INNER CONTAINER OF AN ETHYLENE HEXANOL SOLUTION BROKE DUE TO AN INSUFFICIENT AMOUNT OF CUSHIONING/ ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF THE MATERIAL SATURATED AND LEAKED THROUGH THE 30 GALLON FIBER OUTER DRUM. THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY. THE OESS FIELD PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKING THIS CONTAINER WAS RETRAINED ON THE PROPER LABPACKING TECHNIQUES INCLUDING ADDING SUFFICIENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL.

DRIVER REPORTED TO SHIPPER WITH A CLEAN TRAILER. THE SHIPPER LOADED THE TRAILER, SEALED IT, AND SIGNED THE SHIPPING PAPERS. THE DRIVER LEFT THE PLANT AND WAS EN ROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE'S. THE SECURITY GUARD CALLED DISPATCH TO REPORT A POSSIBLE LEAK ON THE TRAILER. DISPATCH CALLED THE DRIVER AND HAD HIM CHECK FOR A LEAK. UPON INSPECTION, THE DRIVER FOUND THAT THE DOME LID SEAL WAS MISSING. THE DRIVER REPLACED THE SEAL AND TOOK THE LOAD BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE FIRE DEPT. AND HAZMAT TEAM WERE CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE 16 GALLON SPILL.

DEFECTIVE "O" RING ON THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, UTLX 201303, SEPTEMBER 18, 2002, NORTH EAST DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 18, 2002 AT OAK ISLAND YARD IN NEWARK, NEW JERSEY, DURING AN INSPECTION, CSXT HAZMAT, FRA HAZMAT, AND CONRAIL HAZMAT NOTED AN ODOR AROUND TANK CAR UTLX 201303, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED VINYL ACETATE STABILIZED.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S RISK MANAGER AND REACT, AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WHO REPLACED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE IN KIND (REPLACEMENT SUPPLIED BY UNION TANK CAR COMPANY).  ON SEPTEMBER 20, 2002, TANK CAR SECURED AND OKAYED FOR MOVEMENT CAUSE CODE 548 NARRI = 5(4+3+0)X(2+0)=70

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE OFFLOADING AT THE BAX GLOBAL INC.  FACILITY IN PORTLAND, OREGON, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON A METAL PALLET.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM ON (1) 19-LITER STEEL DRUM.  APPARENTLY, THE RELEASE OCCURRED DUE TO THE LID BECOMING LOOSE ON THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT.  BAX GLOBAL INC.  PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE DANGEROUS GOODS BUREAU TO DISCUSS CLEANUP ACTIONS.  PER INSTRUCTION FROM THE DANGEROUS GOODS BUREAU, BAX GLOBAL INC.  PERSONNEL APPLIED SAND TO THE FREE PRODUCT AND PLACED THE WASTE INTO A 5-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  ONE (1) 5-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE BAX GLOBAL INC.  FACILITY IN PORTLAND, OREGON PENDING DISPOSITION.  THE LID WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING  5-GALLON DRUM AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL EIGHT JUGS WERE LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY HALF A CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE CARTONS BEING IMPROPERLY LOADED, CAUSING THEM TO TIP OVER DURING TRANSIT AND FREE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE CAPS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, BOOTIES AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE EIGHT LEAKING JUGS WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED, AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING THIRTY POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED ON A PALLET AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY THE TRAILER WALL, AS A RESULT NO SHROUDING OR DUNNAGE SURROUNDING THE FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AN APRON, DUSTPAN, BROOM, AND AMPHO-MAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING BAG WAS REPAIRED AND WAS FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE YARD MASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN LOCUS POINT, MD REPORTED THAT THE SWITCH CREW REPORTED A STRONG ODOR AROUND TWO TANK CARS ON TRACK R07; GATX53961 AND GATX53987, BOTH ARE RESIDUES, LAST CONTAINED, WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE, CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL. CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED A TECHNICIAN TO INSPECT THE CARS AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS. THE TECHNICIAN MONITORED AROUND THE VALVES OF GATX53961 FOR ORGANIC VAPORS WITH AN HNU METER AND DETECTED A SMALL CONCENTRATION OF VAPORS. HE REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER. HE CHECKED FOR VAPORS AGAIN AND GOT NO READINGS. NO VAPORS WERE DETECTED ON THE GATX53987 BUT THE TECHNICIAN DID "SNUG UP" THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS. THE CARS WERE THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

CSXT'S POLICE DEPARTMENT REPORTED THAT A VANDAL WAS ATTEMPTING TO STEAL ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM TANK CAR GATX 94431 AT THE CSXT RAIL YARD IN PASCAGOULA, MS. THE SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A HOSE HANGING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND REPORTED IT TO THE POLICE COMMUNICATIONS CENTER. THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND CAUGHT THE PERPETRATOR IN THE ACT OF DRAWING PRODUCT OFF THE TANK CAR INTO A 25-POUND PROPANE CYLINDER. THE PERPETRATOR ATTEMPTED TO FLEE BUT WAS APPREHENDED. THE PERPETRATOR LEFT THE VALVE ON THE TANK CAR OPEN AND THERE WAS A VAPOR LEAK WHERE THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE TANK. THE SHIPPER, CHEVRON PRODUCTS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THEY CLOSED THE VALVE, REMOVED THE HOSE AND INSTALLED THE VALVE PLUG. THE TANK WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION FOLLOWING THE POLICE INVESTIGATION.

AT 1800 HRS., SEPT. 11, 2002 WHILE CSX TRANSPORTATION YARD CREW WAS SWITCHING TANK CAR ECUX 374032 (LOAD, PETROLEUM DISTILLATES N.O.S.) IN THE WALBRIDGE, OH RAIL YARD THEY NOTICED PRODUCT SPLASHING OUT FROM THE TOP. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER RESPONDED RESCAR REPAIR OF TOLEDO, OH TO INVESTIGATE. RESCAR REPORTED BACK THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISALIGNED AND REPLACED IT WITH A NEW GASKET. CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVING ONTO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 0020HRS, CSXT'S TRAIN Q28110 WITH 4 ENGINES, 38 LOADS AND 73 EMPTIES DERAILED THE 38TH THROUGH THE 55TH HEAD CARS AT MP QS 129 APPROXIMATELY MILE EAST OF MONTROSE, IL. A GATX 81925, LOAD OF ACETONE, WAS THE ONLY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INVOLVED. THE GATX 81925 WAS DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE FLANGE AND FROM THE MAN-WAY COVER. THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE ON SCENE ESTIMATED THE RATE OF RELEASE ABOUT 2 GALS/MINUTE. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SYSTEMS (HAZMAT) DEPARTMENT RETAINED AN OUTSIDE PROFESSIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO STOP THE RELEASE AND CONDUCT ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OPERATIONS. THE HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MADE BOTH STATE AND FEDERAL SPILL NOTIFICATIONS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AT THE FLANGE OF THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE BUT WAS NOT ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK. AT THE MAN-WAY COVER. PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE MAN-WAY WAS COLLECTED IN A BUCKET AND TRANSFERRED INTO DRUMS. THE TANK CAR WAS ROLLED UPRIGHT STOPPING THE LEAK AND PLACED IN THE CLEAR AT 0730HRS. THE ACETONE WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE DAMAGED TANK CAR INTO HIGHWAY TANKERS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY. THE SPILL AREA WAS EXCAVATED WITH GUIDANCE FROM THE IL EPA AND THE IMPACTED SOILS WERE PLACED INTO 2 ROLL OFF CONTAINERS. CONTAINERS WERE TRANSPORTED TO AN APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY. GATX 81925 WAS CLEANED AND PURGED OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESIDUE ON 09-13-2002.

column168: CSXT YARD CREW AT DEWITT YARD (SYRACUSE, NY), NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAK FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR, UTLX 12198, WHILE SWITCHING. THE CREW NOTIFIED CSXT YARD MANAGEMENT, AND THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED ON THE STORAGE TRACK FOR ISOLATION. MANAGERS FROM CSXT HAZMAT AND CSX TRANSFLO RESPONDED TO INVESTIGATE. THE MANAGER FROM CSX TRANSFLO, FOUND THE ONE ARM LOCK BOLT TYPE FILL HOLE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, HE SECURED THE FILL HOLE BY TIGHTENING THE NUT 4 FULL TURNS. YARD CREW COUPLED TO CAR AND MOVED IT TO CHECK SECUREMENT OF LID, NO LEAKS WERE OBSERVED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE MOVING TANK CAR ECUX 374032 OVER THE HUMP AT STANLEY YARD, TOLEDO, OH, CSXT PERSONNEL OBSERVED LIQUID SPLASH FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED FROM THE MAIN CLASSIFICATION YARD TO AN ISOLATED TRACK. INSPECTION OF THE CAR SHOWED THAT TWO OF THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. NO PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON THE GROUND NEAR OR ABOUT THE CAR. CSXT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED THEM OF THE SITUATION AND THE NEED TO HAVE THE MANWAY LID SECURED BEFORE THE CAR COULD MOVE ANY FURTHER. THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED RESCAR TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS. A RESCAR TECHNICIAN ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION ON 9/9/02 AND FOUND THAT TWO OF THE MANWAY BOLTS HAD NOT BEEN TIGHTENED. THE BOLTS WERE MADE TOOL TIGHT AND THIS SECURED THE MANWAY LID. FINDING NO OTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE CAR, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE AT 1400 9/9/02.

PACKAGE WAS OPEN DUE TO OBVIOUS LEAKAGE. ONE OF EIGHT GLASS BOTTLES OF AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE WAS BROKEN. REQUESTED MSDS FROM SHIPPER. MSDS INDICATED FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS. THEREFORE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING INVESTIGATION. TSA NOTIFIED.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET LISTS A FLASH POINT OF 101-110 F FROM AND MSDS OBTAINED FROM THE WEB SITE. A SECOND MSDS OBTAINED FROM THE MANUFACTURER LISTS A FLASH POINT AT 105 DEGREES FARENHEIT. AS THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD NOT BEEN OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO CONTAIN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE CONTENTS BELIEVED TO BE FLAMMABLE ARE A WAX STAIN. THE TSA HAZMAT AGENT STEVE BRASHER WAS NOTIFIED. FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: AT THE POINT OF DELIVERY, THE RECEIVING LINE WAS ELEVATED SEVERAL FEET ABOVE THE SURFACE OF THE GROUND, THE DRIVER HANDED THE DELIVERY HOSE UP TO A PLANT OPERATOR WHO CONNECTED THE HOSE TO A RECEIVING LINE.  THE FITTING THAT THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO WAS CONSTRUCTED OF ALUMINUM AND THE PRODUCT WE WERE DELIVERING WAS 75% PHOSPHORIC ACID WHICH IS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH ALUMINUM.  WHEN PRODUCT FLOW BEGAN, THE ALUMINUM FITTING BEGAN TO DISSOLVE AND A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID BEGAN DRIPPING FROM THE FITTING.  DELIVERY WAS STOPPED, THE FITTING REPLACED WITH ONE CONSTRUCTED OF STAINLESS STEEL AND THE DELIVERY WAS THEN COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE CAUSE OF THIS SPILL WAS DUE TO THE PLANT USING AN ALUMINUM FITTING FOR THE HANDLING OF PHOSPHORIC ACID.  CUSTOMER PICKED UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND HANDLED DISPOSAL.

THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FOUR HUNDRED GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY SIXTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE ASPHALT OF THE YARD. THE DAMAGE TO THE TOTE WAS DUE TO BEING PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PUT DOWN BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT ON THE ASPHALT. THE SAN ANTONIO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AND THEY USED A FORKLIFT TO PLACE THE LEAKING TOTE ON TOP OF STEEL DRUMS AND THEN USED PUTTY TO PATCH UP THE HOLE TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED ABSORBENTS INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE ASPHALT. KEN CAMPBELL OF ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. CONTACTED HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KS TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. FURTHER CLEANUP DETAILS WILL BE PROVIDED UPON INVOICING. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY, FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED A CARTON OF THE SAME PRO NUMBER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE CARTON BEING CRUSHED DURING HANDLING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND AFFECTED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE LEAKING JUG WAS PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS AND CONTENTS OF THE AFFECTED CARTON WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL TO REPACKAGE AND FORWARD. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1930 PST, SEPTEMBER 10, 2002, LARRY BAKER, AN APRIA EMPLOYEE, STARTED TO MOVE AN APRIA VEHICLE, ISUZU FRR, VIN# JALC4B152Y7007959 WHEN HE REALIZED THAT HE HAD NOT DISCONNECTED THE FILL LINE BETWEEN THE BULK TANK AND THE HL190, NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK, MOUNTED ON THE TRUCK. THE BULK TANK IS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE APRIA OFFICE AND THERE WERE NO OCCUPIED BUILDINGS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. BEFORE HE COULD GET THE VEHICLE STOPPED, OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID BEGAN DRAINING ONTO THE GROUND. HE TURNED OFF THE IGNITION, SET THE EMERGENCY BRAKE AND WENT TO THE SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. HE FOUND THAT THE FILL LINE HAD BEEN SEVERED. THE VALVES ON THE BULK TANK WERE SECURED BUT THE FILL LINE WAS DRAINING FROM THE CARGO TANK. HE WAS NOT ABLE TO REACH THE VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK BECAUSE OF THE VAPOR CLOUD. BAKER THEN RAIN INTO THE APRIA OFFICE AND CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER, JOHN STAUSSER, WHO WAS THE ONLY PERSON IN THE BUILDING. BAKER THEN RETURNED TO THE AREA WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED AND PROCEEDED TO SECURE THE AREA FROM ANY VEHICULAR OR PEDESTRIAN TRAFFIC. UPON BEING ADVISED OF THE SITUATION STAUSSER ATTEMPTED TO REACH HIS SUPERVISOR WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO THE TRUCK TO ACCESS THE SITUATION. UPON REACHING THE TRUCK HE FOUND THAT THE TANK HAD DRAINED OUT AND THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS ALREADY DISSIPATING. STAUSSER VERIFIED THAT THE AREA SURROUNDING THE TRUCK WAS SECURE AND RETURNED TO THE OFFICE TO MAKE CONTACT THE BRANCH MANAGEMENT. ONE OF THE CONTACTS WAS MADE WITH JOE DELMER, BRANCH LOGISTICS SUPERVISOR, WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON HIS ARRIVAL THE VAPOR CLOUD HAD COMPLETELY DISSIPATED. THE AREA WAS SECURED FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE NIGHT, WITH ACCESS NOT PERMITTED UNTIL THE NEXT MORNING TO ALLOW AMPLE TIME FOR A COMPLETE DISPERSION OF ANY OXYGEN SATURATION.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. ONE (1) 220 GALLON TOTE VALVE BROKE OFF BY A FORKLIFT WHEEL WHILE OF THE TERMINAL . THE JERSEY CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. KEN'S MARINE SERVICES OF BAYONNE, NEW JERSEY WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. KEN'S MARINE SERVICES APPLIED SPEEDY DRY TO THE FREE LIQUID ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE AND USED RINSE WATER TO CLEAN THE AFFECTED AREA. KEN'S MARINE SERVICES ALSO PUMPED THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID FROM THE DAMAGED TOTE. FOUR (4) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF RINSE WATER AND FREE PRODUCT, THREE (3) THIRTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF SPEEDY DRY, AND TWO (2) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF SPEEDY DRY WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP. DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: ON 9-9-02, ULRICH CHEMICAL WAS DELIVERING APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 12.5% TO THE BEST WESTERN ROAD STAR INN LOCATED AT 1751 LEXINGTON ROAD IN RICHMOND, KENTUCKY. DURING THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING, THE VALVE ASSEMBLY ON THE CARGO TANK FAILED. THUS, RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 65 GALLONS OF PRODUCT BEING SPILLED  ONTO THE FACILITIES PAVED PARKING LOT. PRIOR TO FULL CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL, SOME OF THE PRODUCT MIGRATED INTO A LANDSCAPED AREA OF THE PROPERTY. NO PRODUCT MIGRATED INTO ANY WATERWAYS OR THE CITIES STORM WATER COLLECTION SYSTEM. ULRICH CONTACTED AND COORDINATED THE SPILL CLEAN-UP WITH THE CITY OF RICHMOND FIRE DEPARTMENT; MADISON COUNTY LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMITTEE AND THE  KENTUCKY DEPARTMENT FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION. PRODUCT THAT WAS SPILLED ONTO THE PARKING LOT WAS ABSORBED AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE LANDSCAPED AREA AND PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 10, 2002 DANA TRANSPORT'S  DRIVER WAS HAULING A TANK TRAILER OWNED BY ITS CUSTOMER COMPTON/ACCIDENTAL THAT WAS LOADED BY THE SHIPPER IN HAHNVILLE, LOUISIANA . THE LOAD WAS DESTINED TO DELIVER IN FRIENDLY WEST VIRGINIA. THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP IN MCNEIL MISSISSIPPI. WHEN HE RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK HE NOTICED A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE OVER THE DOME AREA OF THE TRAILER. THE TRUCK STOP WAS IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED AND SIX OCCUPANTS FROM TWO OF THE HOMES IN THE AREA. THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. US ENVIRONMENTAL IN JACKSON,  MS SENT A TEAM SENT A TEAM OUT TO WORK WITH COUNTY OFFICIALS AND BRING THE INCIDENT UNDER CONTROL. TWO INDIVIDUALS WENT TO A NEARBY HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION BOTH WERE RELEASED NO TREATMENT RENDERED. THE ROAD CAUSE ANALYSIS SHOWED THAT A GASKET UNDER THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE CRACKED.

column168: TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE, A BIG RIG CARRYING A LOAD OF GRAPES CAME OVER THE CENTER LINE AND HIT OUR PROPANE BOBTAIL CAUSING IT TO LOSE CONTROL, HIT A TREE AND LAND ON ITS SIDE. THE CARGO TANK ON OUR BOBTAIL WAS PARTIALLY SMASHED CAUSING THE 3/4" LIQUID VALVE TO LEAK. WHEN CHP ARRIVED ON SCENE THEY CLOSED THE ROAD IN BOTH DIRECTIONS IN A 1/2 MILE RADIUS. A CLEAN-UP COMPANY WAS CALLED IN TO FIX THE LEAK. ONCE THE CREW GOT THE LEAK REPAIRED THEY WERE ABLE TO PUMP OUT APPROX. 1694 GALLONS OF PROPANE INTO ANOTHER BOBTAIL CARGO TANK. THEY THEN BURNED OFF THE REMAINING 290 GALLONS OF PROPANE IN A CONTROLLED ENVIRONMENT, WITH A TOTAL PRODUCT LOSS OF APPROX. 16 GALLONS. THE TOW COMPANY NEEDED TO DISASSEMBLE THE BOBTAIL IN ORDER TO MOVE IT FROM THE SCENE TO BE TAKEN TO THEIR YARD AT THIS POINT THE POLICE REPORT HAS NET BEEN RELEASED.

column168: STEEL DEWAR WAS PICKED UP AT CUSTOMER LOCATION IN FORT COLLINS, CO. AND LOADED/SECURED TO THE WALL OF THE TRAILER WITH ROPE. AT THE TIME OF LOADING, THE DEWAR WAS NOT FOUND TO BE LEAKING. TRAILER WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DENVER SERVICE CENTER (FEDEX FREIGHT) IN COMMERCE CITY. UPON ARRIVAL AND DURING UNLOAD AT THE DENVER SERVICE CENTER, THE DEWAR WAS FOUND TO STILL BE SECURED TO THE TRAILER WALL WITH ROPE AS LOADED. HOWEVER, THE DEWAR WAS AUDIBLY LEAKING AS A LOUD HISSING  SOUND WAS EMANATING FROM THE TOP OF THE DEWAR SOMEWHERE AROUND THE VALVE MECHANISM. CAUSE OF THE LEAK IS STILL UNKNOWN, THOUGH VALVE OR CONTAINER FAILURE IS SUSPECTED. UPON DISCOVERY OF SPILL, ALL PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED FROM THE AREA. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, A MSDS WAS REQUESTED, AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY FOR DISPOSITION AND CLEANUP/HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS. SHIPPER CONTACT (STEVEN BERG@H3R) ADVISED NO DANGER AND CONTACTED AN OUTSIDE AGENCY TO COME OUT AND INSPECT THE DEWAR THE NEXT MORNING. NEXT DAY AFTER INSPECTION, THE DEWAR WAS CLEARED FOR TRANSPORT AND DEWAR WAS THEN MOVED AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

DRIVER USED HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID ALONG WITH ABSORBENT PADS, DIRT, AND OIL DRY .  THE ST. AUGUSTINE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  THE ST. AUGUSTINE FIRE DEPARTMENT OVERPACKED THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  MORAN ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY OF JACKSONVILLE, FLORIDA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE REMAINDER OF CLEANUP. MORAN ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY, ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND DIRT FROM THE AREA.  ALL CONTAMINATED PALLETS WILL BE BROKEN DOWN AND THE TRAILER WILL BE DECONTAMINATED.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED.  THE FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, AND ST. JOHN'S COUNTY LEPC WERE NOTIFIED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A DRUM DOLLY ON THE DOCK FLOOR. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, PATCHED UP, AND WILL BE PLACED INTO ONE, EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED IT WITH A NOTATION OF THE LEAK.  THEY IMMEDIATELY TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS TO ANOTHER DRUM.  EARLIER CARRIER NOTES INDICATE THAT THE DRUM HAD FALLEN FROM A DRUM PICK WHILE IT WAS BEING LOADED ONTO THE DELIVERY TRAILER.

DURING HANDLING ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK THE SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT WAS DAMAGED AND PUNCTURED.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE AND SECURED IT TO A PALLET.  THEY CLEANED UP THE DOCK FLOOR WITH A SPILL PAD.  THE DRUM WAS HELD OFF TO AWAIT INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHEN THIS ARRIVED AT LUMBERTON AND WE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR, IT WAS THEN REALIZED A DRUM WAS LEAKING.  THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THIS WAS REPORTED TO CHEMTREC WHICH CONTACTED EMERENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING.  THEY SENT CONTAMINANT CONTROL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

THE CONSIGNEE OF THE SHIPMENT DOES NOT HAVE A DOCK, SO IT WAS NECESSARY FOR THE DRIVER TO HAVE THE PALLETS CONTAINING THE MATERIAL POSITIONED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER PRIOR TO OFFERING IT FOR DELIVERY. THEY ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO CLEAN THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.

WHILE UNDERWAY, THE DRIVER TEAM WAS ADVISED VIA CB RADIO OF SOMETHING LEAKING FROM THEIR TRAILER.  THEY EXITED THE HIGHWAY AND PARKED IN A REMOTE AREA NEAR A TRUCK STOP. DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE FROM REAR OF TRAILER AND PULLED TO SIDE OF ROAD. FOUND WHAT APPEARED TO BE A TIRE OR BRAKE FIRE.  ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH FIRE USING MULTIPLE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS TO NO AVAIL.  FIRE THEN ENGULFED TRAILER AND IGNITED THIS PRODUCT WITHIN.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED ALONG WITH ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (EMI) TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  AT THIS TIME, IT IS NOT KNOWN WHETHER THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID LEAKED OVER THE TIRE/BRAKE OR IF THE TIRE/BRAKE FIRE CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BURN.  FIRE MARSHAL REPORT NOT YET AVAILABLE.

HM ONE CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY OPERATIONS CENTER, THE ARDEC, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE NRC.  ONCE THE TEAM ARRIVED, THEY SECURED THE TOTES IN THE TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED THE TRAILER TO A NEARBY TERMINAL.  THE MAIN FOCUS WAS ON THE PARKING LOT SO THAT THE BUSINESS COULD OPERATE WITHOUT A PROBLEM.  THE TEAM FINISHED THE PARKING LOT, THEY HAVE TO RETURN TOMORROW TO FINISH THE TRAILER.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 18, 2002, AT APPROXIMATELY 22:40, CSX TRAIN Q53218 DERAILED FOUR BOXCARS IN HUMPHREYS COUNTY, TN ON HIGHWAY 70 EAST OF WAVERLY.  A LOADED TANK CAR OF HEPTANE, PPRX 55117, WAS AHEAD OF THE FIRST DERAILED BOXCAR, BUT WAS NOT DERAILED.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES, AS A PRECAUTION, EVACUATED APPROXIMATELY 200 RESIDENTS FROM THE AREA OF THE INCIDENT.  CSX PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND FOUND PPRX 55117 WAS NOT DERAILED AND THE TANK WAS NOT DAMAGED.  THE TRAIN, ALONG WITH PPRX 55117, WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA AFTER INSPECTION AND THE DERAILED BOXCARS WERE CLEARED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION WAS LIFTED ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2002.

column42: METHANE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (CRYOGENIC LIQUID) OR NATURAL GAS, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (CRYOGENIC LIQUID), WITH HIGH METHANE CONTENT)
column168: TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE, ATLANTA GAS LIGHT COMPANY HAS RECENTLY REBUILT ALL THE VALVES ON THE LNG TANKERS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 16, 2002, THE DRIVER OF A SOUTHEASTERN LNG TRUCKING TANKER TRANSPORTING LNG FROM ATLANTA GAS LIGHT COMPANY'S RIVERDALE PLANT TO CHATTANOOGA GAS COMPANY'S LNG PLANT NOTICED THE VEHICLE BEHIND HIM FLASHING HIS LIGHTS.  WHILE FOLLOWING THE TANKER, THE DRIVER HAD NOTICED THAT THE BACK DOORS AT THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE HAD FROSTED OVER AND A SLIGHT CLOUD WAS COMING FROM THE DOORS.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE FOLLOWING HAD DIALED 911 ON HIS CELL PHONE.  AS THE TANKER DRIVER PULLED OVER, HE REALIZED THAT, MORE THAN LIKELY, THE VALVE LOCATED INSIDE THE DOORS HAD VIBRATED SUCH TO CAUSE IT TO OPEN SLIGHTLY.  ONCE STOPPED, HE PREPARED TO OPEN THE DOORS AND CLOSE THE VALVE.  AT THAT TIME, THE POLICE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TOLD HIM TO GET AWAY FROM THE VEHICLE.  THE POLICE NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT UNIT, CLOSED THE 3500 BLOCK OF AMNICOLA HIGHWAY, AND BEGAN EVACUATING APPROXIMATELY 250 PEOPLE (ACCORDING TO NEWSPAPER REPORTS).  WHEN HAZMAT ARRIVED, CHIEF NICHOLS NOTIFIED CHRIS YOUNG, SUPERINTENDENT OF THE CHATTANOOGA LNG PLANT.  MR. YOUNG, UPON ARRIVAL, DISCUSSED A PLAN TO CLOSE THE APPARENTLY OPEN VALVE WITH CHIEF NICHOLS.  AFTER BEING OUTFITTED IN PROTECTIVE GEAR, MR. YOUNG, ACCOMPANIED BY TWO FIRE FIGHTERS, CLOSED THE VALVE.  THE TANKER THEN RESUMED ITS ROUTE TO THE CHATTANOOGA LNG PLANT WHILE THE ROAD WAS RE-OPENED.  ROAD CLOSURE IS ESTIMATED AT ONE HOUR.  ONCE AT THE PLANT, 8286 GALLONS OF LNG, AN APPROXIMATE FULL LOAD WAS OFF-LOADED. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT NO MORE THAN 5 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE OPEN VALVE. THIS INCIDENT WAS COVERED ON THREE LOCAL CHATTANOOGA TELEVISION STATIONS AND WAS REPORTED ON SECTION B, PAGE 5 OF THE CHATTANOOGA TIMES FREE PRESS.

column168: THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT AND OUT FOR DELIVERY WHEN THE LEAKAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY HAD OCCURRED. THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN REFUSED BY THE RECIPIENT BECAUSE OF THE AFOREMENTIONED LEAKING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE ITEM WAS RETURNED TO THE STATION WHERE IT WAS OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO METAL CAN'S WITH MANUFACTURE'S LABELS THAT INDICATED THAT THEY WERE SOME TYPE OF PAINT RELATED STAIN MATERIAL. APPARENTLY THE LID SEAL ON THE TWO INNER UNITS HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THERE WERE ALSO INDICATOR'S OF EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE ON THE LABELS AS WELL. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE TSA/FAA FOR DISPOSITION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT LYNNE CHARVET/TSA/BUR ON 09/25/2002 AT 13:08 CST. THIS WAS AFTER A VOICE MAIL WAS LEFT AT TSA/LAX ON 09/24 AT 16:57 (CST) INITIALLY REPORTING THE INCIDENT.

THE SUPERVISOR AT THE CAR SHOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN CHARLESTON, SC, REPORTED THAT FRA INSPECTOR, DAVID SNYDER, HAD OBSERVED TANK FPAX 932007, LOAD OF ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, NOS, WITH EVIDENCE THAT HAD BEEN LEAKING AT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR RESCAR TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS. THE RESCAR TECHNICIAN FOUND LIQUID INSIDE THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HOUSING AND SUSPECTED THE VALVE WAS BAD. HE ARRANGED TO RETURN ON MONDAY, 09-16-2002 TO REPAIR OR REPLACE THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. 09-17-2002, RESCAR REPORTED THAT THEIR TECHNICIAN REPAIRED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON 09-16-2002. THE VALVE HAD LOOSE BOLTS INSIDE THE VALVE THAT ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT OF THE VALVE WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. RESCAR MADE THE BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND INSTALLED NEW "O" RINGS. THEY THEN RELEASED IT TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: PASSENGER BAG TAGGED 75-43-14 WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING A STRONG ODOR FOR THE AFT CARGO HOLD.  FSC ORTEGA ADVISED HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE SECURITY ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER SPOKE WITH PASSENGER GOMEZ REGARDING CONTENTS WITHIN HIS BAG.  PASSENGER ADVISED SEO ANDINO THE BAG CONTAINED NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND THE ODOR MAY BE A BOTTLE OF AFTER-SHAVE.  SEO FOUND THE LARGE SOFT-SIDED EXPANDABLE BAG TO CONTAIN A WHITE PLASTIC BAG.  WITHIN THE PLASTIC BAG WAS TWENTY-FOUR .5 FL OZ BOTTLES OF NAIL POLISH.  THREE OF THE BOTTLES OF NAIL POLISH HAD BROKEN CAUSING THE STRONG ODOR.  THE BAG WAS TAKEN OFF THE FLIGHT.  PASSENGER EDUCATED BY THE SEO REGARDING THE FEDERAL REGULATIONS, REPORTING REQUIREMENTS AND POSSIBLE FINES.  THE BAG WILL AIR OUT AND BE SENT ON THE NEXT AVAILABLE FLIGHT.  THE CONFISCATED REGULATED ITEMS WILL BE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION AND IF CLEARED DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  PASSENGER WAS ALLOWED TO TRAVEL TO DESTINATION OF MEDELLIN, COLUMBIA.  THE SPILL OF THE DANGEROUS GOOD DID NOT A CAUSE OF ANY INJURY OR DAMAGE.

column168: (A/B) OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON R0UTE 59 JUST OUTSIDE OF GARRISON, TX WHEN ACCORDING TO WITNESSES HIS TRUCK SUDDENLY SWERVED TO THE RIGHT THROUGH A FARMERS FENCE AND STRUCK A TREE KILLING THE DRIVER INSTANTLY. UPON IMPACT THE TRACTOR CAUGHT FIRE AND CAUGHT THE TRAILER ON FIRE. MOST OF THE LOAD BURNT IN THE FIRE BECAUSE THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS UNSURE WHAT THE MATERIAL ON BOARD WAS AND THEREFORE WERE UNABLE TO TRY TO EXTINGUISH THE BLAZE. I WAS NOTIFIED BY ROMAN OF THE TEXAS COMMUNICATION CENTER (TCC) 936-634-4623 AROUND 21:05 OF THE ACCIDENT AND THE CONDITION OF MY DRIVER. AT THAT POINT I CONTACTED OSI SPECIALTIES  @ 800-809-9998 AND ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE AT THE CRASH SITE. OSI IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THEIR HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUP FROM DOW CHEMICALS IN TEXAS AND THEY WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. ONCE I NOTIFIED OSI I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER(NERC) @ 800-424-8802 AND FILED A REPORT WITH THEM. THE PERSON COMPLETING MY REPORT WAS JACQUELYN ARSENAULT AND THE CASE# SHE GAVE ME WAS 622205. THIS REPORT WAS COMPLETED AROUND 21:35 ON 9/6/02 AT THAT POINT I HAD LIMITED INFORMATION TO GIVE BUT CALLED BACK 9/9/02 TO SUPPLY ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION NEEDED. AFTER REPORTING THE INFORMATION TO THE NERC, I SPOKE TO TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCES CONSERVATION COMMITTEE (TNRCC) REGARDING THE ACCIDENT. THEY INQUIRED WHO WE HAD RESPONDING TO THE SCENE I EXPLAINED THAT DOW CHEMICAL'S EMERGENCY HAZMAT TEAM WAS IN ROUTE AND WE WERE TRYING TO CONTACT A LOCAL HAZMAT CLEAN UP COMPANY TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP AND RESTORATION. THE TNRCC FAXED OVER A LISTING OF SUITABLE COMPANIES FOR THIS JOB. DANDY CONTACTED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (GES) TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP AND RESTORATION. GES WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE TNRCC AS TO WHAT NEEDED TO BE DONE FOR CLEAN UP AND REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL. MOST OF THE PRODUCT WAS DESTROYED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE AND THEREFORE LEFT VERY LITTLE SOIL CONTAMINATION. AT THE COMPLETION OF THE CLEANUP GES SENT SAMPLES OF THE BEFORE AND AFTER SOIL TO BE ANALYZED FOR CONTAMINATION. AS FOR THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT, IT IS STILL UNKNOWN, THE TOWING COMPANY SPECULATED THAT A WHEEL BEARING FAILED. THIS HOWEVER IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION. AS FAR AS WHAT CAN BE DONE TO INSURE THAT THIS TYPE OF EVENT DOES NOT TAKE PLACE AGAIN, UNTIL WE HAVE A DEFINITE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WE REALLY CAN NOT ANSWER THAT QUESTION. IF ANY FURTHER EXPLANATION IS NEEDED PLEASE DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT THE UNDERSIGNED AND I WILL BE GLAD TO HELP IN ANY WAY I CAN.

column168: FILE: 2242-D, SHIPPER: SAFETY KLEEN, AWB# CNP 8885739425 KEM.  ON 09/18/2002 AT 04:16 A CALL CAME IN OF A PACKAGE THAT WAS WET AND NEEDED CHECKED OUT TO SEE IF IT WAS LEAKING AT DOOR "C-10" OF BUILDING "C" LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN JOHN MANNING AND EUGENE LOVAS RESPONDED ARRIVING ON SCENE AT 04:26 AFTER COMPLETING A PRIOR DETAIL.  THE AREA WAS TEMPORARILY EVACUATED UNTIL RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN.  TECHNICIANS LOVAS AND MANNING INSPECTED THE OUTER PACKAGES FOR ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS AND DID NOT FIND ANY WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE AIRBORNE EXPRESS AIR WAYBILL, WHICH DID NOT INDICATE WHAT THE CONTENTS WERE, TECHNICIANS LOVAS OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND DISCOVERED A 5 GALLON WHITE DRUM THAT WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS INDICATED ABOVE.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF MERCURY, ONLY A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED INCLUDING AN ABSORBENT PAD AND SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY AND PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION STEEL DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING TSA INVESTIGATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 04:39

WHILE SHIPMENT WAS EN ROUTE FROM ALBUQUERQUE TO FARMINGTON A SMALL CAP ON TOP OF THE TANK THREADED INWARD UNTIL THE CAP FELL INTO THE TANK.  A GALLON OR LESS SPILLED OUT.  THIS WAS DISCOVERED WHEN UNLOADING BEGAN AT FARMINGTON.  CONSIGNEE AND EMERGENCY NUMBER WERE CALLED.  CONSIGNEE CAME OUT TO INSPECT.  THEY REFUSED FREIGHT BUT STATED THAT SPILLED AMOUNT COULD BE NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  JIM AT EMERGENCY NUMBER AGREED.  WE DID THIS AND WASHED OUT TRAILER TO CLEAN UP.  THE CAPS ON THESE TOTES NEED TO HAVE A STOP ON THEM TO PREVENT CAP FROM FALLING INTO CONTAINER.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: AT 0528 HRS CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE LIVONIA YARD; LIVONIA, LA.  CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN THE HAZMAT TRACK, WITH NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES.  THE SHIPPER, VULCAN CHEMICALS WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED BY DISPATCHING OIL MOP ENVIRONMENTAL AND LOCAL FACILITY PERSONNEL FOR REMEDIATION AND REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD BEEN RUPTURED.  THE DISK WAS REPLACED WITH A COMPOSITION #165 DISK, WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE EXTERIOR SIDES OF THE CAR WERE CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED, WITH ALL GENERATED WASTE COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDINGLY.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

KINCAID, FIELD SUPERVISOR - SHIELD SECURITY, REPORTED A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE CITY OF INDUSTRY YARD IN INDUSTRY, CA.  KINCAID STATED CONTAINER TEXU 369513, WAS LEAKING A FAST DRIP FROM THE BACK DOOR AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND.  MICHAEL JOHNSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  RMCC MADE COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO INDUSTRY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ALSO, THE APPROPRIATE STATE NOTIFICATIONS.  INDUSTRY FIRE DEPARTMENT, RESPONDED TO THE YARD.  TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, WAS CONTACTED BY MGR. JOHNSON AND RESPONDED TO THE YARD.  THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED AND ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS (HYDROCHLOROIC ACID AND PHOSPHORIC ACID) LOST ITS' ENTIRE CONTENTS AND A SECOND DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS (BUTYL CELLOSOLVE & MONOETHANOLAMINE) LOST APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE RELEASES WERE CAUSED BY IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND RELOADED BY THE CONTRACTOR.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: NOLAN, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR JRSX 1018 ENTRAINED, HAD RELEASED SEVERAL HUNDRED GALLONS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID IN THE OGDEN YARD ON TRACK NUMBER FIVE.  HARRY RODABOUGH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM A CRACK ON THE TANKCAR WHERE THE DRAW BAR CONNECTS TO THE TANKCAR.  RMCC MADE NECESSARY STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS.  REGIONAL MANAGER ERNIE SIROTEK ADVISED THAT TWO THOUSAND GALLONS WAS RELEASED. NORMAN SELF, J.R. SIMPLOT COMPANY, SHIPPER, CONTACTED RMCC AND CONFERRED WITH ERNIE SIROTEK, WHO STATED HE WOULD ASSIST IN REMEDIATION.  BECAUSE THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED, IT WAS DECIDED TO MOVE THE CAR TO A LOCATION WHERE A CONTAINMENT PIT COULD BE PREPARED.  DURBANO, CONTRACTOR, WAS CALLED AND THEY PREPARED A PIT ON THE OLD UPFE TRACK.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THAT LOCATION AND THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE VISQUINE LINED PIT. ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE TO HAVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS AS A COMPATIBLE TANKCAR WAS NOT AVAILABLE.  L.W. MILLER TRUCKING WAS NOTIFIED AND SUPPLIED FOUR TRUCKS FOR THE PURPOSE OF REMOVING THE PRODUCT. THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION WAS COMPLETED AT 0130 HRS ON 09/04/2002.  ALL THE WHILE THIS TRANSLOAD OPERATION WAS IN EFFECT THERE WAS A REMEDIATION EFFORT BEING EFFECTED IN THE YARD ON RAIL #4 AND #5 AND THE AREA BETWEEN THE TRACKS AND THE RIGHT OF WAY ROAD TO THE EAST.  PACIFIC WEST WAS CALLED TO CONDUCT THIS PORTION OF THE REMEDIATION EFFORT.  THE REMEDIATION EFFORT WAS COMPLETE WITH THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BEING REMOVED, THE TRACK REMOVED, AND THE PIT BACKFILLED.  ALL OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE AT 1400 HRS ON 09/04/2002.

MIKE GRANT, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, REPORTED LESS THAN ONE PINT OF NAPHTHA, A FLAMMABLE SOLVENT, WAS RELEASED FROM A LOOSE MANWAY COVER OF TANKCAR COCX 292038 WHICH WAS CURRENTLY LOCATED AT THE WEST OAKLAND YARD.  DISCOVERED A SPACER OUT OF POSITION ON THE NUMBER ONE SWING BOLT ON THE MANWAY.  THE SPACER WAS REPOSITIONED AND MANWAY COVER PROPERLY SECURED.  SUBJECT CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WITH DIRECT BILLING TO THE CUSTOMER.  SEAL REMOVED FROM MANWAY COVER.  CHEVCHEM 0188961.  NEW SEAL APPLIED: UPRR CHEM TRAN SAFETY 0000708.

HARRISON GORDON, FOREMAN GENERAL, REPORTED TANKCAR MWSX 29630 LEAKED PRODUCT AT THE FIVE POCKET OF THE ALTON AND SOUTHERN YARD.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP TO CONTAIN THE LEAK AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. GORDON REPORTED HE WOULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER.  AT 12:18 PM, MGR. MILLER REPORTED THE LEAK WAS FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON THE TANKCAR AND HE TIGHTENED AND SECURED THE VALVE.  MR. MILLER ALSO TIGHTENED THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE PLUG THEN SECURED THEM.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Incompatible Product
column168: MARK, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TWO TANKCARS LEAKING PRODUCT.  TANKCAR JRSX 10156 CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS SPLASHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AND DVLX 1023 CONTAINING SULFUR MOLTEN WAS ALSO LEAKING PRODUCT.  MARK ROSS, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH RM CAT, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY TO RESPOND.  TANKCAR JRSX 10156 HAD TWO LOSE MANWAY BOLTS AND ONE LOOSE GASKET AND RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC.  RM CAT, TOOK ONE MANWAY BOLT BACK TO RESHAPE AND REPAIR.  MR. ROSS REPORTED THE TANKCAR WOULD BE READY FOR SHIPMENT LATER IN THE EVENING WHEN THE OTHER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED.  TANK CAR DVLX 1023 HAD A BAD MANWAY GASKET.  RM CAT DID NOT HAVE THE APPROPRIATE TYPE OF GASKET AND ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD HAVE TO PROVIDE THE CORRECT GASKET.  AT 07:31 PM, MGR ROSS ADVISED THAT THE MANWAY ON TANKCAR JRSX 10156 WAS SECURED AND ALL OTHER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED AT 07:10 PM.  THE CONTRACTOR WOULD BE MAKING NECESSARY REPAIRS TO DVLX 1023 AS SOON AS THE CORRECT GASKET WAS RECEIVED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: REXENE MANECKE, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR IAPX 1016, LOCATED IN YARD 1, TRACK 305, WAS SPEWING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  JOHN STEWART, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 7:25 PM, MGR. STEWART REPORTED THE TANKCAR VENTING WAS CAUSED BY AN OPENED NEEDLE VALVE WHICH WAS TURNED THREE TIMES TO STOP THE VENTING.  JOHN, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, CLARK OSWALD, AIR LIQUIDE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: DOYLE GIBBS, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR NATX 75381 LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  MR. GIBBS STATED NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED AND THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 61 IN THE BOOTH YARD.  TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 01:47 PM, MGR. O'BRIEN REPORTED THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM A CORROSION HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR.  AT 03:13 PM, MGR. O'BRIEN STATED THERE WERE TWO LOCATIONS WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BALLAST AND WOULD BE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM CARBONATE.  NO IMPACTS TO WATERWAYS.  THE TANKCAR WAS PATCHED AT 02:45 PM AND TRUCKS WERE EN ROUTE TO TRANSLOAD THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  THE LADING WAS SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS AND THE SITE CLEARED AT 0250 ON 9/10/02.

ON 9/10/02, 1500 HOURS A REPORT WAS RECEIVED FROM THE MANAGER OF INTERMODAL OPERATION REPORTING A POSSIBLE LEAK OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FROM A MIXED SHIPMENT AT THE UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, FRENCH CAMP, CALIFORNIA. AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE LOAD THAT WAS PARKED IN A SEGREGATED AREA AND FLUID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING.  A PH TEST REVEALED A HIGH PH OF 14, WHICH WAS BELIEVED TO BE SODIUM HYDROXIDE BASED ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS.  RMCC MADE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.  PLASTIC AND ABSORBENT WERE PLACED UNDER THE CONTAINER TO PROTECT THE GROUND.  THE EMERGENCY CONTACT ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES WAS MADE.  A MS. STACEY DESHAZO AUTHORIZED MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO REMEDIATE THE LOAD.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED AND FOUND ONE 275 GALLON TOTE HAD FAILED AT THE TOP REAR RIGHT OF THE TOTE.  APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF ZEP MANUFACTURING SUPER DOUG CLEANER CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE HAD SPILLED.  THE METAL CAGE ON THE TOTE WAS IN PLACE AND THERE APPEARED TO BE SOME LATERAL MOVEMENT DURING SHIPMENT.  THE TOTE IN THIS MATTER APPEARS TO HAVE FAILED.  THE CONTAINER WAS RELOADED AND CLEANED.  THE LOAD WAS THEN RELEASED FOR STREET MOVEMENT.  THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN THE TOTE WAS TO BE TRANSLOADED INTO THE NEW TOTE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: NIKI, CHEMTREC, REPORTED SHE WAS CONTACTED BY KASIB RASHADA, CONDUCTOR OF TRAIN AEGNL 09, MR RASHADA ADVISED THAT TANK CAR CELX 3254 WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE DOME AREA.  NICKI ADVISED THE TRAIN WAS IN ARKADELPHIA, AR.  RMCC CONTACTED MR. RASHADA AND HE STATED THE TANK CAR WAS SEVENTEEN CARS FROM THE HEAD END AND THE TRAIN WOULD BE STOPPED AT MP 413 UNTIL PROPER PERSONNEL WERE ON SCENE.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  NIKI ISSUED CHEMTREC REPORT NUMBER 09102002049 TO THE INCIDENT.  AT 11:55 AM DAVE JONES, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS - NLR COMMAND CENTER, REPORTED MIKE AVERY, MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE WAS ENROUTE.  AT 1:55 PM KENNETH SIMPSON, REPORTED THE PLUG ON THE AIR VALVE AND THE PLUG ON THE LIQUID VALVE WERE LOOSE.  MR. SIMPSON TIGHTENED BOTH PLUGS AND THE PRODUCT THAT WAS ON THE HOUSING EVAPORATED.  MR SIMPSON RELEASED THE TRAIN AND WILL INSPECT IT AGAIN WHEN IT ARRIVES AT THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARDS.

column42: PROPIONIC ACID WITH NOT LESS THAN 10% AND LESS THAN 90% ACID BY MASS
column168: ED RICHARD, YARDMASTER, REPORTED GATX 46208 WAS LEAKING A STEADY DRIP FROM THE OUTLET CAP.  THE TANKCAR WAS TEN RAILCARS FROM THE WEST END OF TRACK THREE AT THE RIVERFRONT YARD.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND NOTIFIED SPILL RESPONDERS, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND.  RENALDO SMITH, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THAT THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAD AGREED TO RELEASE THE LEAKING RAILCAR TO BE MOVED FOR REPAIRS.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELOCATED TO AN ISOLATED LOCATION.  SPILL RESPONDERS PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO SLOW, BUT NOT STOP THE LEAK.  EASTMAN CHEMICAL WAS ON SCENE ASSISTING IN THE ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK.  A HOLE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TANK, REQUIRING THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANKCAR TO BE TRANSLOADED.  PRODUCT WOULD BE CAUGHT IN BUCKETS UNTIL THE TRANSLOAD COULD BE COMPLETED.  PRODUCT WAS SUCCESSFULLY TRANSLOADED TO TANK TRUCKS ON 9/13/2002.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT 1008HRS ON 9-14-02, MTO DANNY DENECAMP REPORTED LOADED TANK DCTX 14017 LOCATED ON TRACK 61, KIRBY YARD, SAN ANTONIO, TX TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  WAYBILL INFORMATION INDICATED CAR WAS LOADED WITH CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S., UN1760.  CAR HAD BEEN MOVED AND ISOLATED TO TRACK 63 FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MGR LERCH DISPATCHED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND AND TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STOP RELEASE AND REPAIR CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL OF EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, THE CAR WAS NOTED WITH A DRIED STAINING OF PRODUCT ON SIDES IN THE AREA AROUND THE MAN WAY OPENING. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE MAN WAY GASKET WAS THE WRONG SIZE (TOO BIG), AND WAS CUT AT THE HINGE OF THE MAN WAY COVER.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND MAN WAY CLOSED AND TIGHTENED, WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE SIDES OF THE CAR WERE CLEANED AND THE CAR SET-OUT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION ON 9-16-02.  UPON COMPLETION OF INSPECTION, THE CAR WILL BE RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE SHIPPER, SAL GONZALES, TRANSPORTATION MANAGER OF CHEVRON PRODUCTS, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  MGR ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, PAUL PERSON INSPECTED THE CAR ON MONDAY MORNING AND REPLACED THE GASKET THAT EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL HAD PUT ON THE CAR, AS THAT GASKET HAD ALSO FAILED.  THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS.  MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN DES MOINES, IA, AND MADE CONTACT WITH KEITH HARRIS, CAR FOREMAN, TO DETERMINE THE PROBLEM. MR HARRIS ADVISED THE CAR WAS DRIPPING LIQUID FROM BOTTOM VALVE ON THE TANK CAR AND THERE WAS A SLIGHT ODOR OF ROTTEN EGGS IN THE AREA.  AFTER RESEARCHING THE CHEMICAL, MR. SEKAVEC ADVISED MR. HARRIS TO KEEP ANYONE FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE CAR AS THE PRODUCT DECOMPOSES TO HYDROGEN SULFIDE GAS AND AMMONIA.  CHRIS WILLIAMS, MYO, AT 18TH STREET YARD WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, CONTRACTOR, WOULD BE RESPONDING TO ASSESS THE CAR FURTHER AND ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK.  MR. SEKAVEC HAD RMCC CONTACT CHEMTREC TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER.  JUPITER SULFUR/TESSENDERLO KERLEY AND GET FURTHER INFORMATION ON THE PRODUCT.  CHRIS PAIL MADE CONTACT WITH MR SEKAVEC AND CONFIRMED THE CHEMICAL PROPERTIES AND WAS ADVISED OF THE APPARENT SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  ON ARRIVAL, PERSONNEL .  FROM HAZ-MAT RESPONSE VERIFIED THE CAR WAS PROTECTED AND MADE AN ASSESSMENT.  INITIALLY THERE WAS NO APPARENT ACTIVE LEAK.  LARRY HOME, PROJECT MANAGER, ADVISED MR. SEKAVEC THAT THERE WAS RESIDUE ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR BUT THAT NO ACTIVE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS FOUND.  MR SEKAVEC ADVISED MR HOME TO HAVE A SWITCH CREW COUPLE INTO THE CAR AND SHAKE IT SLIGHTY TO SEE IF THAT WOULD RESTART THE LEAK.  AFTER DOING THAT, MR. HOME ADVISED THAT THE LEAK HAD INDEED RETURNED.  IT APPEARS TO BE COMING FROM THE PLUG IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S CAP.  PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PLUG BUT WERE UNSUCCESSFUL DUE TO THE PLUG BEING CROSS THREADED IN THE CAP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN ASSEMBLY OF A BUCKET AND PLASTIC SHEET MADE TO CAPTURE  ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR WHILE AT THE SAME TIME PREVENTING ANY RELEASE OF PRODUCT TO THE BALLAST.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR AND ITS PREVIOUS LOCATION WERE ALSO CHECKED FOR CONTAMINATION WITH NONE FOUND.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE RESULTS OF THE EXAMINATION AND REPAIR ATTEMPTS.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD BE FORWARD A REPLACEMENT CAP AND PLUG FOR INSTALLATION ON THE CAR.  THE REPLACEMENT ARRIVED AT 9/18/02 AND WAS INSTALLED FOLLOWING REMOVAL OF THE DEFECTIVE CAP.  NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE DETECTED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT FROM THIS INCIDENT AND THE SHIPPER WILL DISPOSE OF THE DEBRIS AND WASTE GENERATED ON THIS INCIDENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: WHILE BEING HANDLED IN NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD AT ALEXANDRIA, LA.  THE SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID DRIPPING FROM BENEATH THE STUFFING BOX COVER FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FOR TANKCAR DCTX 14015.  THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED AT THE YARD WITHOUT INCIDENT OR INJURY.  THE YARDMASTER CONTACTED THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER.  RMCC IN TURN MADE ALL APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS INCLUDING UPRR MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS T. M. ROBINSON, THE ALEXANDRIA FIRE DEPT., THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY AND THE SHIPPER, CHEVRON.  THE OPERATING STEM OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD BECOME DISENGAGED FROM THE VALVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  THE PORTION OF THE STEM THAT NORMALLY STICKS OUT OF THE STUFFING BOX HAD SLIPPED INTO THE TANK, LEAVING AN APPROXIMATELY ONE INCH HOLE WHERE PRODUCT COULD BE RELEASED.  LOUISIANA STATE POLICE SGT. ED BOBBIT AND MASTER TROOPER STEVE CHILDERS ADVISED CHEVRON AND UPRR THAT THE TANK CAR COULD NOT PROCEED UNDER LOAD AND WOULD REQUIRE TRANSLOADING.  MS. JULIE RATCHIE OF CHEVRON INSTRUCTED ROBINSON TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO TANKER TRUCKS AT CHEVRON EXPENSE.  ROBINSON CONTACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENV. SERVICES.  ON WEDNESDAY 9/18/02, EAGLE, UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MR. MIKE TODD TRANSLOADED THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR INTO FOUR TANK TRUCKS WITH OUT INCIDENT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: TERRY, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED LPG PROPANE WAS RELEASED FROM AN UNKNOWN TANKCAR CURRENTLY LOCATED AT THE WEST END OF THE BOWL ON TRACK NUMBER 55 AT THE NORTH PLATTE YARD.  TERRY STATED THE BOWL AREA HAD BEEN EVACUATED AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED.  KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MGR. KEELING INSPECTED TANKCAR GATX 19031 AND DETERMINED THAT A PARTIALLY OPEN VAPOR VALVE AND A LOOSE PLUG ON THE VAPOR VALVE LOCATED ON THE B END OF THE TANKCAR WAS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  MGR. KEELING SECURED THE VAPOR VALVE AND PLUG, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  THE EVACUATION OF THE AREA AT THE WEST END OF THE BOWL WAS LIFTED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM.

MANAGER ERNIE SIROTEK WAS ADVISED THAT CONTAINER FSCU 611810 RELEASED 5 GALLONS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID FROM AN IMPROPERLY SECURED BUNG ON A 55-GALLON POLY DRUM. BUNG WAS RE-SECURED, SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED, AND CONTAINER RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

ON 09/24/02 OXYCHEM CONTACTED TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY TO REPORT THAT CAR NUMBER HOKX7856 HAD LEAKED CHLORINE FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WHILE BEING UNLOADED AT THE DUPONT FACILITY IN LA PORTE, TX. A RESPONSE TEAM FROM DUPONT APPLIED A C-KIT TO THE RELIEF VALVE. AFTER OBTAINING THE REQUISTE MOVEMENT APPROVAL FROM THE FRA, UP MOVED THE CAR FROM THE DUPONT FACILITY IN LA PORTE, TX TO THE OXYCHEM FACILITY IN DEER PARK, TX. THE MOVEMENT WAS ESCORTED BY UP'S AND OXYCHEM'S RESPECTIVE HAZMAT TEAMS ON 9/25/02.

BOB SCHUT, MANAGER, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, WEST COLTON, REPORTED A SWITCHMAN WAS INJURED WHEN TANKCAR RPBX 23601 LEAKED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF SULFURIC ACID FROM AN UNKNOWN LOCATION ON THE TANKCAR. MR.SCHUT STATED THE EMPLOYEE WAS INJURED WHEN THE TANKCAR WAS BEING MOVED FROM THE BOWL TRACK IN THE COLTON YARD, TO THE TRIM TRACK MR. SCHUT STATED THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE LOMALINDA HOSPITAL AND TREATED FOR PRODUCT EXPOSURE TO HIS FACE AND ARMS. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. TOM PARR, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, WAS CONTACTED AND STATED THE EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR FACE AND CLOTHING EXPOSURE TO THE PRODUCT. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR AND FOUND A FILM OF PRODUCT RESIDUE ALONG THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR. THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WAS FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. IT APPEARS THE CAR SUSTAINED AN OVERSPEED IMPACT. DURING THE HUMPING ACTIVITY, WHICH CAUSED A LIQUID SURGE WITHIN THE CAR, FORCING THE PRODUCT UP THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TUBE, RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE TRIM CREW PULLED THE CAR FROM THE BOWL TRACKS, AND SWITCHED IT TO ANOTHER TRACK WITHIN THE TRIM YARD. THE AFFECTED EMPLOYEE WAS STANDING NEXT TO WHERE THE JOINT WOULD BE MADE AND WHEN THE TANK CAR COUPLED INTO THE STANDING EQUIPMENT, THE RESIDUE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR BECAME AIR BORN.SEVERAL DROPLETS OF PRODUCT STRUCK THE SWITCHMAN ON THE FOREHEAD, ARMS, AND CLOTHING. INSPECTION OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE SHOWED NO DEFECTS, AND THE VALVE HAD RESET PER DESIGN. ASBURY ENVIRONMENTAL WAS BROUGHT ON SITE TO CLEAN AND NEUTRALIZE THE RESIDUE ON THE CAR. THE SHIPPER, RHODIA, HAD PLANT PERSONNEL INSPECT THE CAR, AND THEY FOUND NO DEFECTS. AS THERE WAS SOME CONCERN BY RHODIA PERSONNEL OVER DISTURBING THE EXISTING GASKET ON THE FILL HOLE MANWAY, THE CAR WAS NOT OPENED TO DETERMINE IF IT WAS OVERLOADED. THE CAR WAS WEIGHED A SECOND TIME, AND THE SCALE WEIGHTS COMPARED, INDICATION IT WAS NOT OVERLOADED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO DESTINATION. RHODIA TO SHOP THE CAR AND INSPECT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ONCE IT IS RETURNED EMPTY.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED ON A RAINY THURSDAY AFTERNOON ON I-70 WEST OF DALLAS PIKE, WV.  THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN THE ROAD WHEN SUDDENLY THE RENTAL TRUCK HE WAS DRIVING APPEARED TO HYDROPLANE INTO THE MEDIAN AND ROLLED OVER BLOCKING THE EAST BOUND LANES OF I-70.  THE PRODUCT WE WERE TRANSPORTING WAS CALCIUM HYDROCHLORITE (SWIMMING POOL CHLORINE) THE MATERIAL WAS PACKAGED IN SMALL PAILS WEIGHING SIX & SIXTEEN LBS.  MY DRIVER CONTACTED THE OFFICE ONCE THE FIRE AND POLICE WE ON THE WAY.  AT THAT TIME, A GENTLEMAN (GARY O'BRIEN) APPROACHED MY DRIVER IDENTIFYING HIMSELF AS AN EMPLOYEE FOR WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY, A LOCAL HAZMAT CLEAN UP AND RECOVERY OUTFIT.  HE ASKED IF DANDY WANTED HIS COMPANY TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP TO WHICH I REPLIED YES.  I THEN CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO THEM, THE REPORT # IS 09262002072.  GARY O'BRIEN FROM WEAVERTOWN THEN CONTACTED ME AND EXPLAINED IT APPEARED THAT NONE OF THE LOAD WAS RELEASED FROM ITS CONTAINERS.  AFTER THAT CONVERSATION I CONTACTED PPG INDUSTRIES THE MATERIALS MANUFACTURER AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO WHICH THEY SAID THEY WOULD DISPATCH THEIR HAZMAT EMERGENCY CREW JUST TO PLAY IT SAFE.  THE CLEAN UP WENT VERY WELL NO FUEL FROM TRACTOR SPILLED AND A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED IN THE TRAILER TO WHICH THEY ESTIMATED MAYBE 100 LBS.  I BELIEVE THIS WAS COUNTING THE WEIGHT OF THE RECOVERY TARPS THAT WERE USED.  WHEN I LEARNED OF THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AND FILED A REPORT WITH THEM ALSO, THE REPORT # IS 624609.  THE GENTLEMAN I FILED THE REPORT WITH SAID THAT SHOULD I HAVE A QUESTION WHETHER TO REPORT ANY FUTURE SPILLS OR NOT IT IS BETTER TO REPORT THAN NOT.  THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AS TO WHY THE TRUCK HYDROPLANED BUT ONCE A DETERMINATION IS MADE THAN OUR RECOMMENDATION WILL BE GIVEN TO ALL OUR DRIVERS IN THE FORM OF A SAFETY REMINDER.  ALSO OUR SAFETY REVIEW BOARD WILL REVIEW THE ACCIDENT AND A DETERMINATION WILL BE MADE AS TO WHETHER IT WAS A PREVENTABLE ACCIDENT OR NOT AND ANY CORRECTIVE ACTION THAT NEEDS IMPLEMENTED.  A COPY OF THE POLICE REPORT CAN BE FORWARDED UPON RECEIPT FROM THE WEST VIRGINIA STATE POLICE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT GEORGIA GULF AT 2230 ON 9/26/02.  TRAILER LOADED AND OPERATOR CLOSED AND BOLTED DOWN DOME LID.  DRIVER INSTRUCTED TO SCALE OUT OF FACILITY.  DRIVER STOPPED AT 0030 & 1000 ON 9/27/02 FOR TIRE CHECK. EVERYTHING APPEARED TO BE OK.  DRIVER WAS PULLED OVER AT APPROX 11:45 BY LA SHERIFF'S DEPT. OFF OF HWY 1 AND WAS INFORMED THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A REPORT OF A LEAK ON THE TANK.  DRIVER SAW A LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE DRAIN TUBE COMING DOWN FROM THE CRASH BOX.  SAFETY PERSONNEL FROM GEORGIA GULF ARRIVED AND OPENED THE DOME LID.  THEY NOTICED THE DOME GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE AND PART OF IT WAS HANGING IN TRAILER.  GASKET WAS PUT BACK IN PLACE & BOLTED DOWN.  OFFICIAL FROM LA ENVIRONMENTAL DEPT. ARRIVED & INFORMED THAT THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THAT THE LIQUID THAT DRIPPED ON THE ROADSIDE WAS CLEANED UP.  ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER STATED THAT LEAK WAS SMALL AND HAD NO OBJECTION TO DRIVER LEAVING AFTER DOT ARRIVED.  TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND ONLY THING FOUND WAS A MARKER LIGHT OUT TRAILER.  REPORT #573928 PREVENTION AT LOADING FACILITY.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0830 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 21, 2002, APRIA EMPLOYEE TIM VON RUMP, ARRIVED AT THE APRIA BRANCH, 91 DIDION ROAD, ST PETERS, MO AND OBSERVED A VAPOR CLOUD AROUND THE BASE OF THE 1500 GALLON OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, BULK TANK. UPON INSPECTION HE FOUND THAT THERE WAS A LEAK AT PRESSURE BUILDING VALVE. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR, BRIAN MATTHEWS. AN UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPT  WAS MADE TO STOP THE LEAK. THE FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE CONTACTED AS WELL AS BOC GAS COMPANY, WHO IS THE BRANCH SUPPLIER. THE BOC CONTACT WAS ABLE TO ADVISE MATTHEWS ON A PROCEDURE THAT ALLOWED HIM TO CLOSE THE VALVE THAT WAS CAUSING THE LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE HAD BEEN A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 85 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID ONTO THE CONCRETE CATCH BASIN OF THE BULK TANK PAD. THE LEAK HAD BEEN SLOW ENOUGH TO ALLOW THE OXYGEN TO VAPORIZE AND DISSIPATE WITHOUT POOLING. UPON INSPECTING THE TANK THE FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS LEFT THE AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT HAS BEEN REQUESTED BUT TO DATE  HAS NOT BEEN RECEIVED. A GATEWAY GASES TECHNICIAN EXAMINED THE TANK ON 9-23-02 AND WAS UNABLE TO FIND ANY MALFUNCTION WITH THE VALVE WHERE THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED. THE VALVE WAS DISASSEMBLED AND REBUILT FOR SAFETY PURPOSES.

column168: DAVID BETTS RESPONDED TO A SPILL HE DON PPE UTILIZED DECISION TREE RESPONSE SHEET WHICH LED HIM TO CORROSIVE LIQUID.

ON 9-19-02 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00AM, PRELOADER JOHNNY CUMMINS NOTICED A WET SPOT ON THE SIDE OF A PACKAGE.  THE SUPERVISORS, DAVID HARRIS & SHAWN WILLIAMS WERE NOTIFIED.  THEY RETRIEVED THEIR GOGGLES, GLOVES, APRONS, BOOTS, DECISION TREE, AND SPILL TUB FROM DMP.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE, THEY NOTICED SHIPPING PAPERS AND A DOT DIAMOND LABEL.  WHILE USING THE DECISION TREE, THEY PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB AND SET IT OUTSIDE THE DOORWAY OF DMP FOR THE SAFETY OF THE EMPLOYEES.  THE PACKAGE WAS CHECKED ON PERIODICALLY AND WHEN THE PRELOAD AND DRIVERS LEFT, SHAWN WENT OUTSIDE TO RETRIEVE THE PACKAGE.  AS HE SET IT IN THE DMP PROCESSING AREA, HE NOTICED IT STARTING TO SMOKE.  HE NOTIFIED HIS MANAGER, ROB MADRZYKOWSKI, OF THE SITUATION.  UPON VERIFICATION, THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED AND AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER, REACT ENVIRONMENTS WAS CALLED.  REACT ARRIVED AND CONTAINED THE PACKAGE, TRANSPORTED IT AND DISPOSED OF IT .  REACT STATED THAT THE PACKAGE, HYDROCHLORIC ACID, GOT WET FROM THE WEATHER WHICH CAUSED THE FUMING.  THIS REACTION IS ALSO STATED ON THE MSDS.  NO EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED AND ALL DMP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. ALL THREE MANAGEMENT EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE SPILL ARE CURRENT DESIGNATED RESPONDERS.

column168: REVISED DESCRIPTION - PLCX 129208 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE RECEIVING YARD AT SELKIRK, NEW YORK.  CSXT FOREMAN PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAKING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AREA.  CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK AND ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE LEAKING VALVE.  THE VALVE COULD NOT BE REPAIRED IN THE YARD.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE STATIONARY LEAK CONTAINMENT AREA AND THE CAR WAS PREPPED FOR TRANSFER.  THE CAR WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER RAIL TANK CAR- NATX300392, USING TOP-TO-TOP TRANSFER METHOD.  THE TRANSFER TOOK 4.75 HOURS.  VISUAL INSPECTION WAS MADE BY M.C. BETHGE, CSXT HAZMAT, WHO FOUND NO APPARENT CAUSE FOR THE LEAKAGE, ALL BOLTS AND NUTS WERE TIGHT. IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE FLANGE AREA ABOVE THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE CAR WAS SENT TO THE MECHANICAL SHOP SO THAT THEY COULD SEND IT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED AN ODOR EMITTING FROM CONTAINER KLFU 115365, A LOAD OF ETHYL MERCAPTAN. THE CONTAINER WAS STILL ON THE TRAIN LOCATED ON TRACK 808. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR AND NOTED AN ODOR FROM THE CENTER AREA OF THE STACK CAR, BUT NO VISIBLE LEAKS. THE CONTAINER WAS OFF-LOAD FROM THE RAIL CAR AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INTERIOR INSPECTION. THE LADING CONSISTED OF METAL 55 GALLON CLOSED HEAD DRUMS, FLOOR LOADED THROUGHOUT THE 40 FOOT CONTAINER. ODORS WERE NOTED TO BE STRONGER WITHIN THE CONTAINER. INTERIOR INSPECTION FAILED TO LOCATE ANY LEAKING DRUMS. ARRANGEMENTS  WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO OFF LOAD AND INSPECT THE DRUMS. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES WERE NO SITE DURING THE REMOVAL PROCESS. SEVERAL DRUMS WERE NOTED TO HAVE STRONGER ODORS, WHICH WERE SET ASIDE. THE DUST COVERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE BUNGS, AND THE BUNGS INSPECTED FOR PROPER TORQUE. A TOTAL OF 8 BUNGS WERE SEMI LOOSE TO WHERE THEY COULD BE WRENCH TURNED AN ADDITIONAL 1/4 TURN. AS A PRECAUTION, ALL OF THE DRUMS BUNGS WERE INSPECTED, TORQUED AS NEEDED , AND THE DUST COVERS REAPPLIED. THE DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER, WHICH THEN SAT FOR 24 HOURS, AND REINSPECTED. ODORS WERE PREVALENT THE FOLLOWING DAY. THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND WIPED DOWN A SECOND TIME WITH A DECON SOLUTION. A TOTAL OF 7 DRUMS STILL HAD STRONG ODORS EMITTING FROM THEM. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, THEN SECURED FOR VESSEL TRANSPORTATION. THE FOLLOWING MORNING THE CONTAINER WAS REINSPECTED AND ONLY SMALL TRACE ODORS WERE DETECTED. AS THE MATERIAL WAS GOING FOR EXPORT, THE VESSEL OPERATOR WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING. THE VESSEL OPERATOR AGREED TO ACCEPT THE CONTAINER FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

AT 02:17 AM, MARK HANRAHAN, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, ADVISED HE HAD INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND A FOG AROUND THE CAR. MR. HANRAHAN FURTHER ADVISED THAT FOG DID NOT SMELL LIKE AMMONIA. column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: MOTOR CARGO DRIVER CLIFF GUDGEL ARRIVED AT GE INTERLOGIC AT 11:10AM ON 9-26-02 TO DELIVER PRO#051-0472319-1. AFTER COMPLETING THE DELIVERY CLIFF DISCOVERED THAT THE BATTERY, PRO#0600866645-3 HAD TIPPED OVER IN TRANSIT AND WAS LEAKING ACID ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. CLIFF CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND GE'S DOCK DOOR TO MINIMIZE PERSONNEL EXPOSURE. CLIFF CHECKED OUTSIDE AND FOUND THAT ACID WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND. GE INTRELOGIC CALLED 911 AND TUALATION VALLEY FIRE & RESCUE WAS DISPATCHED. CLIFF NOTIFIED MOTOR CARGO DISPATCHER JASON THRELFALL AND JASON CALLED FIRST STRIKE. GE'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ASSISTED CLIFF TO PROTECT A STORM-DRAIN THAT WAS NEAR THE TRUCK AND TO ISOLATE THE AREA. WHEN TVF&R ARRIVED THEY CALLED FOR THE EVACUATION OF GE INTERLOGIC'S FACILITY. ONCE THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED TVF&R HAZMAT TEAM #9 OPENED THE TRAILER, UNLOADED THE OTHER FREIGHT ONTO GE'S DOCK AND PARTIALLY UPRIGHTED THE BATTERY TO STOP THE LEAKING. THE INCIDENT WAS THEN TURNED OVER TO FIRST STRIKE. FIRST STRIKE'S TEAM COMPLETED THE UPRIGHTING OF THE BATTERY, AND CONTAINED THE REMAINING SPILLED MATERIAL. THE CONTAMINATED FREIGHT WAS RELOADED AND THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO MOTOR CARGO'S PORTLAND FACILITY. FIRST STRIKE CAME TO THE PORTLAND TERMINAL ON 09-27-02 TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER AND FREIGHT.
